  "prompt": "How does the Aereo antenna work?",
  "response": "Aereo was a company that provided a unique television broadcasting service. It allowed users to watch live TV online and record shows using a cloud digital video recorder (DVR) service. The Aereo antenna system played a critical role in this service.\n\nHere's a breakdown of how the Aereo antenna system worked:\n\n1. **Tiny Antennas**: Aereo used thousands of tiny antennas, each about the size of a dime. When users signed up for the service, they were assigned their own individual antenna. These antennas were housed in data centers in the regions where Aereo offered its service.\n\n2. **Signal Reception**: Each miniature antenna was capable of receiving over-the-air broadcast signals from local television stations. Essentially, these antennas functioned like traditional TV antennas, capturing signals from the air.\n\n3. **Individual Assignment**: One of the key legal arguments made by Aereo was that each user had a dedicated antenna, which acted just like the personal TV antennas people have on their rooftops. This individual assignment was intended to comply with broadcast laws, asserting that Aereo was not rebroadcasting but simply providing infrastructure for personal antenna use.\n\n4. **Internet Streaming**: Once the antenna captured the broadcast signal, it was digitized and transmitted over the internet to the user\u2019s device. This allowed users to watch TV via their computers, tablets, or smartphones.\n\n5. **Cloud DVR**: In addition to streaming live TV, Aereo provided a cloud DVR service where users could record shows and access them later. The recorded content was stored on Aereo's servers and could be watched at any time, much like traditional DVR services.\n\nAereo's innovative approach exploited a perceived loophole in broadcast television laws, arguing that by using individual antennas assigned to each subscriber, they were legally capturing and transmitting TV signals. However, this led to significant legal challenges, including a Supreme Court case in 2014, which ultimately ruled against Aereo, shutting down its service. The court determined that Aereo\u2019s method of streaming broadcast television was essentially like cable companies, who must pay licensing fees to the broadcasters.",
